ritish Bluejacket as both patriotic defender and dutiful husband and father stood in sharp contrast to the stereotypic image of the brave but bawdy tar of the Georgian navy.This book will be essential reading for students of British imperial history, naval and military history, and gender studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMasculinity. 0aSailorszGreat BritainxHistory. 4aStudies in Imperialism 2017. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / General.2bisacsh  aAge of Empire.  aBritish Bluejacket.  aBritish society.  aCrimean War.  aEdwardian Britain.  aFirst World War.  aGeorgian navy.  aVictorian Britain.  abawdy tar.  aclass dimensions.  adebauched sailor.  ademocratization.  aimperial competition.  amass culture.  anaval manhood.  anaval philanthropic organisations.  anaval temperance movement.  anon-commissioned naval men.  aradical transformation.  aworking-class.1 aConley, Mary A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152611765640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526117656423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526117656/original  a978-3-11-128363-0  Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles